>
  <p>The long-duration ECG, or Holter ECG, involves continuously recording the heart's electrical activity for 24 hours or more, using a portable device worn by the patient.</p>

  <p>This examination detects intermittent heart rhythm disorders, often absent during a standard resting ECG.</p>

  <p>The R-Test is an alternative allowing prolonged monitoring, up to one week.</p>

  <p>Unlike the Holter, recording is not continuous but triggered either automatically by the device when an anomaly is detected, or manually by the patient when experiencing symptoms. This approach detects more spaced or unpredictable rhythm disorders.</p>
</DetailLayout>
